{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538481"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:28:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:28:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16191"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16191","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16191"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.02,0.63,0.08,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8882"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112486"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8882","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8882"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16191"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94517"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4373"},{"type":"tags","id":"4534"},{"type":"tags","id":"6364"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21147"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45687"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112486"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the antenatal clinic for her first pregnancy booking visit at 12 weeks\u0027 gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes only pregnancy multivitamins. Her mother has type 2 diabetes. She works as an accountant. Her body mass index is 32 kg/m2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Routine antenatal screening blood tests are performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer HbA1c is 6.8% (51 mmol/mol). Her oral glucose tolerance test results are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFasting plasma glucose: 7.2 mmol/L (\u0026lt;5.3 mmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1-hour glucose: 13.8 mmol/L (\u0026lt;10.6 mmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2-hour glucose: 11.2 mmol/L (\u0026lt;9.0 mmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stress hyperglycaemia","Physiological pregnancy changes","Overt diabetes in pregnancy","Early gestational diabetes","Laboratory error"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis woman presents with elevated HbA1c and markedly abnormal glucose tolerance test results at her first antenatal visit. The combination of risk factors (obesity, family history) and significantly elevated glycaemic markers strongly suggests previously undiagnosed type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOvert diabetes in pregnancy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis. This condition may be diagnosed if any of the following criteria are met: fasting plasma glucose \u2265 7.0 mmol/L or 2-hour post-glucose \u2265 11.1 mmol/L following a 75 g two-hour oral glucose tolerance test; HbA1c \u2265 6.5% (\u2265 48 mmol/mol); and/or random plasma glucose \u2265 11.1 mmol/L in the presence of clinical signs or symptoms indicative of hyperglycaemia. This condition is important to distinguish from gestational diabetes as it is a more aggressive form of hyperglycaemia and much more likely to progress to type 2 diabetes mellitus postpartum. This distinction is important to make as intensive treatment is required. Pre-existing type 2 diabetes mellitus, whilst likely, cannot be definitively diagnosed until confirmatory postpartum glucose assessment has been performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEarly gestational diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E is defined as diabetes first occurring in pregnancy before 20 weeks\u0027 gestation and meeting the following criteria: fasting plasma glucose \u2265 5.3-6.9 mmol/L; 1-hour post-glucose \u2265 10.6 mmol/L; and/or 2-hour post-glucose \u2265 9.0-11.0 mmol/L during a 75 g two-hour pregnancy oral glucose tolerance test. Whilst gestational diabetes is the most common cause of diabetes overall in pregnancy, in this case, the marked hyperglycaemia is reflective of overt diabetes in pregnancy. Gestational diabetes arises due to hormonal influences particularly from the placenta, resulting in increasing insulin resistance. Hyperglycaemia rapidly resolves following delivery of the placenta.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStress hyperglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is a transient elevation in blood glucose due to acute illness or stress. It would not cause a persistently elevated HbA1c, which reflects longer-term glycaemic control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysiological pregnancy changes\u003C/strong\u003E actually tend to lower HbA1c slightly in early pregnancy due to increased red blood cell turnover. The degree of elevation seen here cannot be explained by normal pregnancy physiology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaboratory error\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given the concordance between both the HbA1c and all three glucose tolerance test results, along with the presence of significant risk factors for type 2 diabetes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEarly recognition of overt diabetes in pregnancy is crucial as these women have increased risks of congenital anomalies, miscarriage, and other pregnancy complications. They require urgent referral to a multidisciplinary diabetes in pregnancy team for optimisation of glycaemic control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HbA1c \u22656.5% (48 mmol/mol) in early pregnancy suggests overt diabetes in pregnancy rather than gestational diabetes.","Universal screening for gestational diabetes should occur at booking and 24-28 weeks gestation.","Risk factors for diabetes include obesity, family history, and certain ethnic backgrounds."],"references":["Sweeting, A., Hare, M.J., de Jersey, S.J., Shub, A.L., Zinga, J., Foged, C., Hall, R.M., Wong, T. and Simmons, D. (2025). Australasian Diabetes in Pregnancy Society (ADIPS) 2025 consensus recommendations for the screening, diagnosis and classification of gestational diabetes. Medical Journal of Australia, [online] 1(1). doi:https://doi.org/10.5694/mja2.52696."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94517"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16191"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94517"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-01T18:38:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-01T18:38:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8882"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112486"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"